Chicken bone broth, just an extra word for chicken stock
Stock is not made with bone-in chicken
You pressure cook/slow cook bone-in chicken for hours. (I pressure cooked 3 hours)
You need all the bone and marrow juices to flow through
Bone broth is a marketing term for real stock
Yes In store when you buy "stock" it didn't have the gelatin content from the bones
Because of minimum requirements to save money
So they started making real stock, but calling it bone broth to charge a premium
Bone broth is just closer to the actual stock you make in restaurants or from scraps
And, even worse, you only need 90-120 minutes to make it

but, theres still a difference between basic stock and bone stock
im not sure why the correction was necessary
No there isn't they are the same
you can make stock without bone
Which store bought stock is closer to
And with the exception of a few stocks, the most frustrating lie (well rather it was a misunderstanding) you only need 2 hours to get like 98% out of it

They asked me to do ribs in the smoker today.
they were tasty but i wish i could get more smoke in 'em
@clovepod what temp did you pull at?
internal temp? i don't measure that actually
i do 3-2-1, 3 hours smoke, 2 hours braise, 1 hour with sauce all at around 225F in the smoker
plenty tender but i want more smoke to go in
you should watch the internal temp, when doing bbq (smoking, not cold-smoking) you want to aim at trying to keep it between 170-180f as long as possible
180f is when the collagen starts to burn, 160 is when it starts to melt, 173ish is where it rendering best
so you want to hold it at internal at that temp till the texture where you want, time wise I don't recall as I don't BBQ that much
though, a braise post-smoke, will likely kill off a lot of that smoke
I'd forget the braise, smoke it right, sauce it for the last 15-30 minutes of the smoking
unless you doing pork belly burnt ends then you saucing them longer
The other thing you can do, but it harder to nail without experience is to let it rest after smoking, then reheat IN the sauce when serving
